cocos2d::Texture2D addImage crashes if fed a bad cocos2d::Image

Confirmed to crash with Cocos2d-x 3.10...
Sorry I didn't test with Cocos2d-x 3.11.

How to reproduce:

```
static cocos2d::TextureCache mytexturecache;

+(cocos2d::Texture2D*)getAdTexture2dFromUIImage:(UIImage*)uiimage {
    NSData *objCImageData = NULL; // This doesn't make sense but is just to reproduce crash later. Normally I would get NSData from UIImage...
    cocos2d::Image *cocos2dxImage = new cocos2d::Image();

    const bool LOADEDCORRECTLY = cocos2dxImage->initWithImageData(objCByteData, objCImageData.length);

    // Purposelly we do not check the return value of LOADEDCORRECTLY - it will fail of course in this case, but if we don't check it the addImage below will crash.

    free(objCByteData);

    auto texture2d = mytexturecache.addImage(cocos2dxImage, "unused"); // Crashes here

    return texture2d;
}
```

Above all, please consider the code given below:

> Texture2D::setDefaultAlphaPixelFormat(Texture2D::PixelFormat::RGBA4444);
> Director::getInstance()->getTextureCache()->addImageAsync("HelloWorld.png", [this](Texture2D * texture) {
>     Sprite *sprite = Sprite::createWithTexture(texture);
>     this->addChild(sprite);
> });
> Texture2D::setDefaultAlphaPixelFormat(Texture2D::PixelFormat::RGBA8888);

Obviously, I wanna to create a texture which pixel format is set to RGBA4444, but unfortunately, the code did not work correctly, because in most of the time when the image finish loading, the default pixel format is back to RGBA8888.

An easy and of course non-side-effect way to solve the problem is to store the defaultAlphaPixelFormat in AsyncStruct and use the stored value to create the texture. I do this job in this pull request. Please review and accept it. Thank.

When a relatively long (3-4 seconds) sound effect is playing while a burst of little sounds are playing, the long sound likely will stop its execution. This happens on Android (5.1.1) and does NOT happens on iOS.

The bug can be reproduced with this code to add to Hello World proejct:

```
bool HelloWorld::init()
{
    if ( !Layer::init() )
        return false;

    schedule(schedule_selector(HelloWorld::playLongSound), 2.0f);
    schedule(schedule_selector(HelloWorld::playShortSound), 0.25f);
    return true;
}

void HelloWorld::playLongSound(float dt) 
{
    auto engine = CocosDenshion::SimpleAudioEngine::getInstance();
    engine->playEffect("long.wav"); // 3-4 seconds
}

void HelloWorld::playShortrSound(float dt) 
{
    auto engine = CocosDenshion::SimpleAudioEngine::getInstance();
    engine->playEffect("short.wav"); // < 1 second
}
```

There's a bug in AssetsManagerEx that can cause invalid state of assets update. In any circumstances where decompressDownloadedZip failed, there's no way for the game to recover from this error. The only solution is to uninstall and reinstall the game.

```
void AssetsManagerEx::onDownloadUnitsFinished()
{
    // Finished with error check
    if (_failedUnits.size() > 0)
    {
        // Save current download manifest information for resuming
        _tempManifest->saveToFile(_tempManifestPath);

        decompressDownloadedZip();

        _updateState = State::FAIL_TO_UPDATE;
        dispatchUpdateEvent(EventAssetsManagerEx::EventCode::UPDATE_FAILED);
    }
    else
    {
        updateSucceed();
    }
}
```

The problem might be caused after writing the temp manifest, AssetsManager won't be able to retry on files that fails in decompression. To reproduce the bug:
1. Start update with AssetsManagerEx
2. Trigger download failure
3. Just after temp manifest has been saved and decompression started, kill the game
4. AssetsManagerEx won't be able to detect the failure and resuming the update without previous assets

This problem might also occurs in updateSucceed.
